Yes, there is indeed some *magic* that will cancel the previous delay on each new click (I think that&#39;s what you&#39;re after)

You need to use a `Subject` at the class level, and use `next` on the subject for each click. The `subject` should be set up in the `constructor` (or `ngOnInit`) as follows, with the `tap` operators inside the **pipe**

```
this.subject.pipe(
    switchMap(value =&gt; {
        return timer(1000).pipe(...)
    }),
    tap(...)
).subscribe()
```

The switchMap will cancel the previous timer on each subsequent click

Note: `timer` with an integer value works the same as a `delay`, but is itself an observable, rather than an operator

In your `func pickerView(_ pickerView: UIPickerView, numberOfRowsInComponent component: Int)` method you return a value based on the basis of a number of `if ... else` statements.  These may cover all your possible scenarios but the compiler can&#39;t infer that, and can see a possibility where all four checks fail and therefore no value is returned.

There are a few approaches to fixing this:

1. after the last `if` put in a fatalError to crash out
```
//cut earlier code for brevity
  else if categorySC.isEnabledForSegment(at: 4) {
            return jobsSonstiges.count
  }
  fatalerror(&quot;Invalid segment logic&quot;)
}
```

2. Return a random number, on the basis that if your logic is correct it the code flow should never get that far:
```
//cut earlier code for brevity

  else if categorySC.isEnabledForSegment(at: 4) {
            return jobsSonstiges.count
  }
  return 999
}
```

3. Omit the last `if` check on the basis that it is the only possible value left, and just return the value:
```
    func pickerView(_ pickerView: UIPickerView, titleForRow row: Int, forComponent component: Int) -&gt; String? {
        if categorySC.isEnabledForSegment(at: 1) {
            return jobsHaus[row]
        }else if categorySC.isEnabledForSegment(at: 2) {
            return jobsGarten[row]
        }else if categorySC.isEnabledForSegment(at: 3) {
            return jobsBetreuung[row]
        }else {
            return jobsSonstiges[row]
        }
    }
```

My preference, at least during development, would be for option 1 so that I find out if I&#39;ve made a logic error.

